Global Outlook.title: Federal Reserve Policy Focuses on Sustained Inflation Control
Global Outlook.text: The Federal Reserve's upcoming policy meeting is under intense market scrutiny, with current analyst surveys indicating that rate cuts are not widely anticipated before June. This cautious outlook reflects the central bank's commitment to seeing more definitive evidence of sustained inflation cooling before adjusting its monetary stance. Amidst these policy deliberations, discussions have also emerged regarding potential candidates for future Fed leadership, which could influence long-term economic strategy.

Global Outlook.title: Yen Surges on Intervention Speculation as Authorities Conduct Rate Checks
Global Outlook.text: The Japanese Yen experienced a sharp and rapid appreciation against the U.S. dollar, rebounding significantly after earlier weakness, fueled by strong speculation of impending currency market intervention. This dramatic movement was triggered by reports of the New York Federal Reserve conducting "rate checks" with market participants, a recognized precursor to official action by Japanese authorities to stabilize the yen. Traders are now on high alert for further measures from Japan's Ministry of Finance to counter excessive yen depreciation.

Global Outlook.title: China Tech Stocks Considered a Dollar Hedge Amid Earnings Focus
Global Outlook.text: Chinese technology stocks are being evaluated by some market participants as a potential hedge against fluctuations in the U.S. dollar, with investor attention simultaneously directed toward upcoming corporate earnings. This strategic view underscores the dynamic interplay between currency movements, technological sector performance, and broader economic narratives. The focus on earnings reports will provide further clarity on the resilience and growth prospects of these companies in the current global economic environment.

links.title: China tech seen as dollar hedge, with focus on earnings, Fed

Global Market.text: The Dow Jones Industrial Average concluded a topsy-turvy week in negative territory, with Intel's stock sliding significantly. This downturn was largely attributed to Intel's cautious outlook, which dampened broader market sentiment. The tech sector, in particular, felt the pressure from the semiconductor giant's revised guidance.

Global Tech.title: NVIDIA Ends MSRPs, Signaling Price Hikes and Market Shift
Global Tech.text: NVIDIA is reportedly discontinuing its "Open Price Program" (OPP), effectively ending Manufacturer's Suggested Retail Prices (MSRPs) for its GPUs. This strategic shift indicates that AIB partners will have greater flexibility in pricing, potentially leading to higher street prices. This move comes as China is reportedly preparing orders for NVIDIA's H200 chips, underscoring strong global demand for advanced GPUs, even as production of certain models like the GeForce RTX 5070 Ti is reportedly being reduced.

Global Tech.title: Google Expands AI Initiatives Across Retail, Enterprise, and Healthcare
Global Tech.text: Google is aggressively expanding its AI strategy, with its Gemini Enterprise AI poised to drive significant corporate overhauls by 2026. This includes leveraging agentic AI to unify retail shopping and service experiences at events like NRF 2026. These initiatives highlight Google's commitment to embedding advanced AI capabilities across diverse sectors, moving beyond its traditional search domain into high-value enterprise and consumer-facing applications.

Global Tech.title: Intel Shares Tumble Amid Manufacturing Snags and High AI Investment Costs
Global Tech.text: Intel's stock has significantly declined following disappointing financial results and persistent manufacturing setbacks that are impeding its turnaround efforts. The company's reported losses exceeded forecasts, signaling ongoing operational challenges. These issues are largely attributed to supply chain snarls and the substantial costs associated with heavy investments required to compete in the burgeoning AI chip market. The cumulative effect of financial pressures and production hurdles risks eroding investor confidence in Intel's long-term comeback strategy despite its strategic focus on AI.
